collection.description: This collection features our conversations throughout the State of Maine held with educators, students, community members, and major Maine industry professionals. We are asking what youth will need to thrive personally, civically, and economically in the Maine of 2050. The collection is expanding daily, so check back!
collection.title: Maine ED 2050

highlights.description: This is a concern within our school. We have too many students that are not receiving their most basic of needs, which does not allow them to access further learning.
Our students need to be supporting in seeing how they affect their community, positive or negative. I wonder how much they actually realize this in their life.
This is concerning that students lack independence. The need for constant adult support is a struggle for the students and the teachers.

building more options for children and working to help the community see that we need to build this relationship so we have more tradesmen work available for those who traditional schooling does not work for

As I continue to read and think about this....is their lack of "independence" because they are so conditioned that they have to be perfect. If they are not perfect they are not worthy? The social emotional effects of lacking independence because they are so worried about being wrong or doing it wrong.

Involvement of parents
This is crucial for students to grow and know that education is important.
This came up quite a bit throughout our conversation and the impact it has on a students confidence, independence and learning.
Access to early interventions, childcare, and less stress to parents.

I am sure the parents that worked on these questions are the ones highly involved in school, but what can we do to encourage the rest of the community? How can they see how important the schools are, support the schools and know/understand they are supporting the future.
